From: recmeet
Subject: [PATCH] Clamp topk to size in TopkIndex to avoid heap-buffer-overflow

When `OfflineSpeakerDiarizationPyannoteImpl::FinalizeLabels` calls TopkIndex
with `k = speakers_per_frame[i]` and `size = num_cols` of the powerset
matrix, k can exceed size on short or degenerate inputs (e.g. a single
short voiced frame with the segmentation model claiming more active
speakers than there are powerset columns).

The unfixed TopkIndex passes `topk` directly to `std::partial_sort`:

    std::partial_sort(vec_index.begin(),
                      vec_index.begin() + topk,   // past end when topk > size
                      vec_index.end(), ...);

`std::partial_sort` requires the middle iterator to be in `[begin, end]`.
When `topk > size`, `begin + topk > end` and partial_sort enters undefined
behavior, reading and writing past the end of the (size-N) vector. With
ASAN's redzones this is caught as a heap-buffer-overflow; without ASAN
the past-the-end read silently corrupts an adjacent chunk header, which
manifests as a SIGABRT or SIGSEGV at session destruction time inside
onnxruntime's Graph destructor (the corrupt chunk gets double-freed when
the Graph's internal hashtable destructs).

Recmeet hit this reliably on short recordings (~44 sec) with a single
dominant voice, where the segmentation model produced degenerate frames.
The crash rate was also modulated by parent-process heap layout (e.g.
tray running vs not). See the recmeet repro:

    LD_PRELOAD=/usr/lib/libasan.so.8 \
        recmeet --reprocess /path/to/short-clip --no-summary --no-daemon

ASAN report excerpt (call chain):

    READ of size 4 ... heap-buffer-overflow
      #5 sherpa_onnx::TopkIndex<int> math.h:115
      #6 OfflineSpeakerDiarizationPyannoteImpl::FinalizeLabels
            offline-speaker-diarization-pyannote-impl.h:624
      #7 OfflineSpeakerDiarizationPyannoteImpl::Process
            offline-speaker-diarization-pyannote-impl.h:180

Fix: clamp topk to [0, size] before the partial_sort call. The return-
value clamp (`k_num = min(size, topk)`) was already present but only
affected the size of the returned vector, not the partial_sort itself.
A negative topk would invoke the same UB and is now defended too. When
k_num == size the partial_sort with middle == end already fully sorts
vec_index, so the return path moves it instead of constructing a copy.

Upstream PR: k2-fsa/sherpa-onnx#3628.
 sherpa-onnx/csrc/math.h | 14 ++++++++++++--
 1 file changed, 12 insertions(+), 2 deletions(-)

--- a/sherpa-onnx/csrc/math.h
+++ b/sherpa-onnx/csrc/math.h
@@ -110,15 +110,25 @@

 template <class T>
 std::vector<int32_t> TopkIndex(const T *vec, int32_t size, int32_t topk) {
+  // Clamp topk to [0, size]: std::partial_sort(begin, begin + k, end, cmp)
+  // requires k in [0, end-begin]. Callers (e.g. FinalizeLabels in
+  // offline-speaker-diarization-pyannote-impl.h) can pass topk > size
+  // on short/degenerate inputs; the unclamped call invokes undefined
+  // behavior by reading past the end of vec_index. A negative topk would
+  // be UB for the same reason.
+  int32_t k_num = std::max<int32_t>(0, std::min<int32_t>(size, topk));
   std::vector<int32_t> vec_index(size);
   std::iota(vec_index.begin(), vec_index.end(), 0);

-  std::partial_sort(vec_index.begin(), vec_index.begin() + topk,
+  std::partial_sort(vec_index.begin(), vec_index.begin() + k_num,
                     vec_index.end(), [vec](int32_t index_1, int32_t index_2) {
                       return vec[index_1] > vec[index_2];
                     });

-  int32_t k_num = std::min<int32_t>(size, topk);
+  if (k_num == size) {
+    // partial_sort with middle == end fully sorts vec_index; skip the copy.
+    return vec_index;
+  }
   return {vec_index.begin(), vec_index.begin() + k_num};
 }

